<paragraph blockId="2.[173,660,194,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,361,1018,1039]" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Biological Data.</emphasis>
This species inhabits the disturbed pine-oak forest located at 
<quantity box="[508,590,1044,1065]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.114" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" unit="m" value="2114.0">2,114 m</quantity>
elevation on the southwestern slope of Popocatépetl volcano. Both specimens were attracted to a mercury vapor light trap in September. The date of their capture is very late in the season for 
<taxonomicName box="[173,296,1177,1198]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[173,296,1177,1198]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Phyllophaga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in comparison with the usual phenology of the genus in central 
<collectingCountry box="[467,538,1204,1225]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(May–July).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="169" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[173,660,194,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,296,1230,1251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moron" authorityYear="2013" box="[309,514,1230,1251]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aragoni">
<emphasis box="[309,514,1230,1251]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Phyllophaga aragoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[173,230,1257,1278]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scissa">
<emphasis box="[173,230,1257,1278]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">scissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group as defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Moron &amp; Diversidad &amp; Phyllophaga Harris" box="[521,659,1257,1278]" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" pagination="1 - 27" refId="ref4579" refString="Moron, M. A. 2003. Diversidad, distribucion e importancia de las especies de Phyllophaga Harris en Mexico (Coleoptera: Melolonthidae) [pp. 1 - 27]. In: Estudios sobre Coleopteros del Suelo en America (A. Aragon, M. A. Moron, and A. Marin, editors). Publicacion especial Benemerita Universidad Autonoma de Puebla, Puebla, Mexico." type="book chapter" year="2003">Morón (2003)</bibRefCitation>
and is similar externally to 
<taxonomicName authority="Saylor" authorityName="Saylor" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plairi">
<emphasis box="[466,659,1283,1304]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Phyllophaga plairi</emphasis>
Saylor
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bates)" baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[287,555,1310,1331]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scissa">
<emphasis box="[287,474,1310,1331]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Phyllophaga scissa</emphasis>
(Bates)
</taxonomicName>
. However, the pronotal and elytral punctation of 
<taxonomicName box="[554,634,1336,1358]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plairi">
<emphasis box="[554,566,1337,1358]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[580,634,1337,1358]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">plairi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is denser than that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moron" authorityYear="2013" box="[369,473,1363,1384]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aragoni">
<emphasis box="[369,381,1363,1384]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[396,473,1363,1384]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">aragoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while the clypeal shape of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moron" authorityYear="2013" box="[275,385,1390,1411]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aragoni">
<emphasis box="[275,288,1390,1411]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[306,385,1390,1411]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">aragoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also less bilobed than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[204,295,1416,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scissa">
<emphasis box="[204,217,1416,1437]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[235,295,1416,1437]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">scissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The distal half of the parameres of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moron" authorityYear="2013" box="[202,303,1443,1464]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aragoni">
<emphasis box="[202,303,1443,1464]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">P. aragoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much shorter and narrower than in the other two species, and the apex of the sclerotized aedeagal support is very different between the three species: narrowed and briefly curved in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[290,382,1549,1570]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scissa">
<emphasis box="[290,382,1549,1570]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">P. scissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[403,489,1549,1570]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[197,237,642,661]" captionTargetBox="[189,637,205,619]" captionTargetId="figure-656@6.[173,659,183,648]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 24–25. Lateral view of the genital capsule of Phyllophaga species. 24) P. scissa. 25) P. plairi. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4893174" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4893174/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
); truncate with lateral spurs in 
<taxonomicName box="[345,428,1576,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plairi">
<emphasis box="[345,428,1576,1597]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">P. plairi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[448,529,1575,1596]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[197,237,642,661]" captionTargetBox="[189,637,205,619]" captionTargetId="figure-656@6.[173,659,183,648]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 24–25. Lateral view of the genital capsule of Phyllophaga species. 24) P. scissa. 25) P. plairi. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4893174" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4893174/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
); and broad and curved in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moron" authorityYear="2013" box="[332,438,1602,1623]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aragoni">
<emphasis box="[332,438,1602,1623]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">P. aragoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[457,524,1602,1623]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[175,215,901,920]" captionTargetBox="[158,1154,183,895]" captionTargetId="figure-387@1.[151,1171,183,916]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1–7. Phyllophaga aragoni. 1) Head and pronotum; 2) Male protarsal claw; 3) Female genital plates, ventral view; 4) Parameres, distal view; 5) Complete genital capsule, lateral view; 6) Complete genital capsule, dorsal view; 7) Detail of apex of inner sac, distal view. Scale bars = 2 mm, except in Fig. 2 = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4893166" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4893166/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). The 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[600,659,1602,1623]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Phyllophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scissa">
<emphasis box="[600,659,1602,1623]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">scissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group is currently under study by the author, including a number of undescribed species represented by few individuals from Mexican mountains.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="169" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[707,1193,194,374]" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,845,194,215]" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is named after my friend Agustín Aragón García, professor of the Benemérita Universidad Autónoma de 
<collectingRegion box="[1091,1158,247,268]" country="Mexico" name="Puebla" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Puebla</collectingRegion>
, an enthusiastic promoter of basic and applied studies of scarab beetles in the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[1030,1098,300,321]" country="Mexico" name="Puebla" pageId="2" pageNumber="169">Puebla</collectingRegion>
, who has obtained many important records of new and rare Scarabaeoidea.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
